@PeMa, sure.

When using the example provided by @Chuck Nuris the xml looks like this

```
&lt;TripList&gt;
  &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
  &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
  &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
&lt;/TripList&gt;
```

When working with xml the (more accepted) way of doing things in general is:

```
&lt;TripList&gt;
  &lt;Trips&gt;
    &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
    &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
    &lt;Trip&gt;...&lt;/Trip&gt;
  &lt;/Trips&gt;
&lt;/TripList&gt;
```

While working with the object:

```
class TripList {
   List&lt;Trip&gt; trips;
}
```

Because the more general way to use XML is to **wrap** this list in the `&lt;Trips&gt;` element, the default functionality for Jackson XML is to expect:

The name of the variable `trips` to match the wrapper element `&lt;Trips&gt;` when (de)serializing.  When there is no wrapper element `&lt;Trips&gt;` in this case then you need to tell Jackson that the list of `&lt;Trip&gt;` are not wrapped.

When working with wrapping you can:
- turn it off `@JacksonXmlElementWrapper(useWrapping = false)`
- change the name `JacksonXmlElementWrapper(localName = &quot;MyTrips&quot;)`

based on what you want or have to deal with your example being.

